SLIDE 1 — INTRODUCTION

“Good afternoon everyone.

Today I’ll be presenting the Streamlit App Enhancement work that I implemented in the Snowflake environment.

This enhancement focuses on automating audit column updates and improving the update process through a user-friendly Streamlit application.

The goal of this work was to reduce manual effort, improve consistency, and simplify the overall update process for users.”

SLIDE 2 — EXISTING PROBLEM

“Before implementing the Streamlit application, users had to manually update column values directly in backend tables.

For example, if someone wanted to change minimum or maximum display date values for a table, they needed to manually write and execute SQL update statements.

In addition to updating the date values, audit columns such as UPDATE_DATE and UPDATE_USER also needed to be maintained correctly.

This process required technical knowledge and increased the possibility of manual errors.

To simplify this process, a Streamlit-based UI solution was developed where users could update values directly through an interface without manually writing SQL queries.”

SLIDE 3 — INITIAL STREAMLIT APPLICATION

“Here, this screenshot shows the initial version of the CFG_VW_CONTROL Streamlit application.

The app connects to the CFG_VW_CONTROL table, which stores configuration details for reporting views.

This table contains information such as PROGRAM_NAME, VIEW_NAME, MIN_DISPLAY_DATE, MAX_DISPLAY_DATE, USER_STORY, COMMENTS, DATABASE, and SCHEMA details.

These values help control how data flows through reporting views based on configured display date ranges.

Users could search records using Program Name or View Name and directly update display date values through the UI.

The editable fields included values such as MIN_DISPLAY_DATE, MAX_DISPLAY_DATE, USER_STORY, and COMMENTS.

This helped reduce dependency on manually writing SQL update statements and simplified backend table maintenance.”

SLIDE 4 — AREAS IDENTIFIED FOR IMPROVEMENT

“After reviewing the existing application, several areas for improvement were identified during testing and validation.

One major area was improving audit column handling and update consistency.

For example, UPDATE_DATE and UPDATE_USER columns were still editable, which could lead to inconsistencies.

In addition, all rows were being updated even when values had not changed.

These areas created opportunities to improve automation, optimize update processing, and strengthen audit reliability.”

SLIDE 5 — ENHANCEMENT GOAL

“The main goal of these enhancements was to improve automation, audit reliability, and update efficiency within the application.

The enhancements focused on automatically handling UPDATE_DATE and UPDATE_USER values, restricting manual editing of audit columns, and ensuring that only modified rows were updated in Snowflake.”

SLIDE 6 — UPDATE_DATE ENHANCEMENT

“One enhancement I implemented was automating the UPDATE_DATE audit column.

Previously, users could manually edit this value, which could lead to inconsistencies.

To improve audit reliability, UPDATE_DATE was removed from editable fields and automatically assigned using Snowflake’s current_timestamp() function.

This ensures that every update reflects the latest system timestamp automatically.”

SLIDE 7 — UPDATE_USER ENHANCEMENT

“Another enhancement involved automating the UPDATE_USER audit column.

Instead of manually entering user information, the application now automatically captures the logged-in Streamlit user session information.

This improves audit tracking accuracy and reduces manual input errors.”

SLIDE 8 — KEY ENHANCEMENT

“One of the key enhancements involved improving how updates were processed within the application.

The application now tracks edited rows using Streamlit data editor change tracking.

Only modified rows are captured into a smaller dataset, and only those changed rows are updated in Snowflake.

This improved efficiency and reduced unnecessary database updates.”

SLIDE 9 — KEY ENHANCEMENT CONTD..

“In addition, the application was enhanced to identify and update only modified rows.

Instead of updating the entire dataset, only rows changed by the user are processed.

This prevents unnecessary database updates and improves overall application performance.”

SLIDE 10 — ISSUE IDENTIFIED AFTER DEPLOYMENT

“After deployment, an issue was identified related to Snowflake’s maximum supported date value, which is 9999-12-31.

While Snowflake supports this value, Pandas had difficulty processing this far-future date value during conversion.

This caused data type mismatch errors during the update process for those records.”

SLIDE 11 — SOLUTION FOR DATE HANDLING

“To resolve this issue, I implemented custom date normalization logic.

The solution explicitly handles Snowflake edge-case dates such as 9999-12-31 and 1900-01-01 before Pandas conversion occurs.

This prevented conversion failures and maintained compatibility between Streamlit, Pandas, and Snowflake.

This enhancement improved overall application stability, compatibility, and reliability.”

SLIDE 12 — DEPLOYMENT

“After successful testing and validation in the development environment, the enhancements were deployed to the production environment.

The updated application now provides a more efficient, reliable, and user-friendly process for managing backend table updates and audit tracking.

These enhancements also improved update accuracy and reduced manual maintenance effort.”

